@startuml 19-message-ordering
title JOTP: Message Ordering Guarantees (FIFO Mailbox Semantics)
skinparam backgroundColor #f0f0f0
skinparam sequence {
    BoxBackgroundColor LightBlue
    LifeLineBorderColor DimGray
    LifeLineBackgroundColor White
}

participant Client
participant "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
participant "Proc<S,M>\n(message loop)"
participant Logger

autonumber

note over Client, Logger
  FIFO Mailbox Semantics:
  - All messages from ANY sender
    are ordered in arrival sequence
  - Messages NOT delivered out-of-order
  - State handler sees deterministic sequence
end note

note over Client, Logger
  SCENARIO: Three clients send messages
  in rapid sequence. Proc must see
  all three in order.
end note

Client ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": offer(Msg-A)
note right of "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
  T=0µs: Msg-A enqueued
end note

Client ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": offer(Msg-B)
note right of "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
  T=1µs: Msg-B enqueued
end note

Client ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": offer(Msg-C)
note right of "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
  T=2µs: Msg-C enqueued
  Queue: [A, B, C]
end note

"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": poll()
activate "Proc<S,M>"

"Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)" ->> "Proc<S,M>": return Msg-A
note right of "Proc<S,M>"
  T=100µs: Message loop
  begins processing
end note

"Proc<S,M>" ->> Logger: log("Processing Msg-A")
"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Proc<S,M>": handle(state, Msg-A)

note right of "Proc<S,M>"
  State updates based on A
  state = applyMsg-A(state)
end note

"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": poll()
"Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)" ->> "Proc<S,M>": return Msg-B

"Proc<S,M>" ->> Logger: log("Processing Msg-B")
"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Proc<S,M>": handle(state, Msg-B)

note right of "Proc<S,M>"
  State depends on prior state from A
  state = applyMsg-B(state)
  Ordering is CRITICAL for correctness
end note

"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": poll()
"Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)" ->> "Proc<S,M>": return Msg-C

"Proc<S,M>" ->> Logger: log("Processing Msg-C")
"Proc<S,M>" ->> "Proc<S,M>": handle(state, Msg-C)

note right of "Proc<S,M>"
  Final state depends on
  A → B → C sequence
  Not A → C → B (would be wrong)
end note

deactivate "Proc<S,M>"

---

note over Client, Logger
  ADVANCED: Causal Ordering in State Machines

  State machine transitions create causal chains:
  Event-A → EventTimeout-A → User-Reply-A

  Mailbox preserves this causality:
  - StateTimeout actions insert events
  - Those events queued AFTER user events sent first
  - Ensures causality not violated
end note

participant StateMachine

StateMachine ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": offer(UserEvent-X)
note right of "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
  User event arrives
end note

StateMachine ->> StateMachine: state transition\n→ action(SetStateTimeout)
StateMachine ->> "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)": insertEventAfterTimeout(StateTimeout-X)

note right of "Mailbox\n(LinkedTransferQueue)"
  Timeout inserted
  Queue: [UserEvent-X, StateTimeout-X]
  (timeout will fire ~100ms later)
end note

note over Client, Logger
  GUARANTEE: Causal ordering is preserved
  - User events arrive first
  - Timeouts fire only after delay
  - No message reordering violates causality
  - State machine logic remains deterministic
end note

@enduml
